# Neural Machine Translation by Jointly Learning to Align and Translate
<cite>- Dzmitry Bahdanau, Kyunghyun Cho, Yoshua Bengio</cite>

| Publisher | Container | Year | URL |
|---|---|---|---|
|  | ICLR | 2015 | [Link]()

---
## Abstract
Neural machine translation is a recently proposed approach to machine translation. Unlike the traditional statistical machine translation, the neural machine translation aims at building a single neural network that can be jointly tuned to maximize the translation performance. The models proposed recently for neural machine translation often belong to a family of encoder–decoders and encode a source sentence into a ﬁxed-length vector from which a decoder generates a translation. In this paper, we conjecture that the use of a ﬁxed-length vector is a bottleneck in improving the performance of this basic encoder–decoder architecture, and propose to extend this by allowing a model to automatically (soft-)search for parts of a source sentence that are relevant to predicting a target word, without having to form these parts as a hard segment explicitly. With this new approach, we achieve a translation performance comparable to the existing state-of-the-art phrase-based system on the task of English-to-French translation. Furthermore, qualitative analysis reveals that the (soft-)alignments found by the model agree well with our intuition.

"Most of the proposed neural machine translation models belong to a family of encoderdecoders (Sutskever et al., 2014; Cho et al., 2014a), with an encoder and a decoder for each language, or involve a language-specific encoder applied to each sentence whose outputs are then compared (Hermann and Blunsom, 2014)." ([Bahdanau et al 2014:1](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=1))

_대부분 NMT 모델은 encoder-decoder 세트에 속함 ([note on p.1](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=1))_

"A potential issue with this encoder-decoder approach is that a neural network needs to be able to compress all the necessary information of a source sentence into a fixed-length vector." ([Bahdanau et al 2014:1](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=1))

_이 것의 잠재적 이슈는, 문장의 모든 정보를 ==fixed-length vector로 압축해야 한다는 것!== ([note on p.1](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=1))_

"Each time the proposed model generates a word in a translation, it (soft-)searches for a set of positions in a source sentence where the most relevant information is concentrated." ([Bahdanau et al 2014:1](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=1))

"The most important distinguishing feature of this approach from the basic encoder-decoder is that it does not attempt to encode a whole input sentence into a single fixed-length vector." ([Bahdanau et al 2014:2](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=2))

_문장을 하나의 fixed-length vector로 인코딩 하는게 아니다. ([note on p.2](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=2))_

"We show this allows a model to cope better with long sentences." ([Bahdanau et al 2014:2](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=2))

_fixed-length vector에 압축하지 않아도 되어서 긴 문장에도 잘 적용된다! ([note on p.2](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=2))_

"From a probabilistic perspective, translation is equivalent to finding a target sentence that maxy imizes the conditional probability of given a source sentence , i.e., . y x arg maxy p(y j x)" ([Bahdanau et al 2014:2](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=2))

"the use of neural networks to directly learn this conditional distribution" ([Bahdanau et al 2014:2](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=2))

_conditional probability 구하는데 NN 사용 ([note on p.2](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=2))_

"the proposed approach of jointly learning to align and translate" ([Bahdanau et al 2014:2](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/LWX8U3LW?page=2))

"Hence, we propose to use a bidirectional RNN (BiRNN, Schuster and Paliwal, 1997), which has been successfully used recently in speech recognition (see, e.g., Graves et al., 2013)." ([Bahdanau et al 2016:4](zotero://open-pdf/library/items/A9YYV49Y?page=4))

## 3. Learning to Align and Translate

![Pasted image 20211111142939.png](data:image/png;base64,)

The context vector $c_i$ is, then, computed as a weighted sum of these annotations $h_i$:

$$
c_i = \sum_\limits{j=1}^{T_x}{a_{ij}}{h_j}
$$


$$
a_{ij} = {
\exp(e_{ij})
\over
\sum_\limits{k=1}^{T_x}\exp(e_{ik})
},
$$
where
$$
e_{ij} = {a(s_{i-1}, h_j)}
$$
is **an alignment model** which scores ==how well the inputs around position $j$ and the output at position $i$ match.== The score is based on the RNN hidden state $s_{i-1}$ (just before emitting $y_i$, Eq. (4)) and the  
j-th annotation $h_j$ of the input sentence.
